The federal government and United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) have launched the State of World Population (SWOP Report 2020), with emphasis on the need to remove obstacles that undermine equality of human rights for women and girls across the globe. Speaking at the launch yesterday in Abuja, the acting chairman of National Population Commission (NPC), Dr. Tayo Oyetunji, said the report reaffirmed the equality of human rights for women and men in society and the family. The virtual launching was organised in collaboration with the UNFPA with the theme, “Against my will, defying the practices that harm women and girls and undermine equality.” Oyetunji noted the rights of women and girls are often violated against their will either directly or indirectly, saying such violations could also be seen in harmful practices that women and girls are subjected to. He explained that in Nigeria, 19 per cent of women between the ages of 15-19 have begun child bearing, 14 per cent have given birth, and 4 per cent are pregnant with their first child due to early marriages, adding the prevalent rate of female genital mutilation has remained high in Nigeria at 20 per cent for women and 19 per cent for girls 0-14 years of age (NDHS 2018).